Merge pull request #534 from pmw57/master

Console color updates for Chrome, Firefox, and Internet Explorer too.

Internet Explorer console color support

As setting the colors on IE's console is not an option, we can use
console.info for good messages, and console.error for errors.

As Internet Explorer only returns info about its console when the dev
tools are active, it can be helpful to have the console open before
loading the page. Either that, or you can reload the page after opening
the console.

Chrome and Firefox console color support

Chrome and Firefox provide console colors via CSS style formatting.

Chrome started mimicking Firebug's %c option around 3 years ago:
http://trac.webkit.org/changeset/130941

Details on how to use console colors are found at
http://developer.chrome.com/devtools/docs/console-api#consolelogobject-object
and https://getfirebug.com/wiki/index.php/Console.log

Fix alternative node.js runtimes for mocha
highlight hit lines

Fix alternative node.js runtimes for mocha

This is related to mochajs/mocha#1585, yamadapc/mocha-spec-cov-alt#3 and
possibly other issues in other repositories.

`mocha` spawns a child process `_mocha` in order to support custom
node.js flags being passed into it.

The newest version of `mocha` (2.2) uses `process.execPath` rather than
`process.argv[0]` to spawn the child. This is meant to be able to have
better support for things like `io.js`. Because of that,
`process.argv[0]` in this line of `blanket` is set to the absolute path
to the node.js/io.js/etc. executable, rather than `node`.

This fixes that problem by comparing the `basename` of `process.argv[0]`
with a list of appropriate executable names.

Merge pull request #255 from mohamedmansour/master

Exit instrumentation when user redefines "window"

Exit instrumentation when user redefines "window"

The redefine of “window” in the middle of the function breaks code
coverage because it depends on “window”. The reason why it breaks it is
because JavaScript moves all variables to the top of the function. When
adding instrumentation, var'ing “window” will cause it to be null from
the start of the function that window._$blanket depends on.

Allow pattern to be a function

is more complicated than what can be easily added to a regular
expression. In these cases, you can set a function as the pattern. This
function will get executed with the filename and can perform any user
logic to determine if the file should be instrumented.
